[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":1326},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F24\u002Fpython-from-js-23-class\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F24\u002Fpython-from-js-23-class\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F24\u002Fpython-from-js-23-class\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F24\u002Fpython-from-js-23-class\u002F":1303,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F24\u002Fpython-from-js-23-class\u002F":1312},"\u002Fpython\u002F20210924\u002F2221702568\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":1285,"date":1286,"description":1287,"extension":1288,"lang":1289,"meta":1290,"navigation":290,"path":1291,"readingMinutes":1292,"seo":1293,"standalone":1294,"stem":1295,"tags":1296,"tldr":1300,"updated":1286,"url":1301,"__hash__":1302},"content\u002Fen\u002FPython\u002Fpython-from-js-23-class.md","Learning Python From a JS Angle (23): Classes — and Why JavaScript Isn't Quite OOP","1002510326",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":1277},"minimark",[11,16,25,29,32,35,41,44,51,54,63,134,137,140,148,151,426,429,588,591,597,606,616,628,631,640,657,663,691,694,700,703,730,740,746,752,755,828,851,883,914,944,975,981,993,1037,1040,1091,1094,1161,1164,1177,1191,1198,1204,1208,1224,1228,1231,1235,1267,1273],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19,20,24],"p",{},"This one's a bit of a breather. We're just going to have a quick, low-key chat about Python's ",[21,22,23],"code",{},"class"," syntax. Nothing too heavy, I promise.",[12,26,28],{"id":27},"object-oriented-programming","Object-Oriented Programming",[17,30,31],{},"Python is an object-oriented language (Object-oriented programming, usually shortened to OOP). So... what does object-oriented actually mean? And is JavaScript object-oriented too?",[17,33,34],{},"Honestly, this question bugged me for a long time. Some people swear JavaScript is object-oriented, others insist it isn't, so before we touch Python let me untangle it a little. Instead of talking myself in circles, let's just pull up some docs. Here's how Wikipedia describes \"object-oriented programming\":",[36,37,38],"blockquote",{},[17,39,40],{},"It may contain data, attributes, code, and methods. An object is an instance of a class. OOP treats objects as the basic unit of a program, packaging code and data together to improve reusability, flexibility, and extensibility. The code inside an object can access and frequently modify the data associated with that object. In object-oriented programming, a computer program is designed as a collection of objects that relate to one another.",[17,42,43],{},"Yeah, I'm guessing that read like word soup. It's pretty stiffly worded:",[17,45,46],{},[47,48],"img",{"alt":49,"src":50},"Me, pretending I understood that","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FPython\u002F%E5%BE%9E%20JavaScript%20%E8%A7%92%E5%BA%A6%E5%AD%B8%20Python\u002F1630032487036.png",[17,52,53],{},"But you might be thinking, \"Object-oriented... so this is related to objects, right?\"",[17,55,56,57,59,60,62],{},"And the answer is \"Yep, very much so.\" It's tied closely to objects. On top of that, object-oriented development usually starts by declaring a class — that's the ",[21,58,23],{}," keyword — and a ",[21,61,23],{}," is basically an abstract object. For example, you might have a Dog class, and that Dog class holds all the basic traits a dog has. The shape of it might look something like this:",[64,65,70],"pre",{"className":66,"code":67,"language":68,"meta":69,"style":69},"language-cmd shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","class Dog\n  public methods:\n    bark()\n    claws:\n  private methods:\n    coat color:\n    breed:\n    tail length:\n    name:\n    scientific name:\n","cmd","",[21,71,72,80,86,92,98,104,110,116,122,128],{"__ignoreMap":69},[73,74,77],"span",{"class":75,"line":76},"line",1,[73,78,79],{},"class Dog\n",[73,81,83],{"class":75,"line":82},2,[73,84,85],{},"  public methods:\n",[73,87,89],{"class":75,"line":88},3,[73,90,91],{},"    bark()\n",[73,93,95],{"class":75,"line":94},4,[73,96,97],{},"    claws:\n",[73,99,101],{"class":75,"line":100},5,[73,102,103],{},"  private methods:\n",[73,105,107],{"class":75,"line":106},6,[73,108,109],{},"    coat color:\n",[73,111,113],{"class":75,"line":112},7,[73,114,115],{},"    breed:\n",[73,117,119],{"class":75,"line":118},8,[73,120,121],{},"    tail length:\n",[73,123,125],{"class":75,"line":124},9,[73,126,127],{},"    name:\n",[73,129,131],{"class":75,"line":130},10,[73,132,133],{},"    scientific name:\n",[17,135,136],{},"(I would never admit I came up with that class by staring at my own dog.)",[17,138,139],{},"And from that Dog class we can keep inheriting downward to give each one its own specifics — coat color is brown, breed is mixed, tail length is none, and so on. So you can also think of object-oriented programming as a blueprint concept.",[17,141,142,143,147],{},"By that logic, JavaScript is object-oriented too, then? Basically yes — JavaScript is object-oriented, but it's ",[144,145,146],"strong",{},"prototype-based"," object-oriented. I know that already sounds like a tongue twister, so let's just look at some examples.",[17,149,150],{},"Here's some Java, just thrown together quickly for comparison:",[64,152,156],{"className":153,"code":154,"language":155,"meta":69,"style":69},"language-java shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","class Home\n{\n    public String father;\n    public String mother;\n    Home(String a, String b) {\n        father = a;\n        mother = b;\n    }\n    public void myFather(){\n        System.out.println(\"my father is \" + father);\n    }\n}\n\npublic class main\n{\n    public static void main(String[] args)\n    {\n        Home myHome = new Home(\"jack\", \"judy\");\n        System.out.println(myHome.father); \u002F\u002F jack\n        System.out.println(myHome.mother); \u002F\u002F mother\n        myHome.myFather(); \u002F\u002F my father is jack\n    }\n}\n","java",[21,157,158,167,173,184,193,214,225,235,240,253,274,279,285,292,304,309,336,342,374,388,401,416,421],{"__ignoreMap":69},[73,159,160,163],{"class":75,"line":76},[73,161,23],{"class":162},"sWyjQ",[73,164,166],{"class":165},"s_sBn"," Home\n",[73,168,169],{"class":75,"line":82},[73,170,172],{"class":171},"sMAXC","{\n",[73,174,175,178,181],{"class":75,"line":88},[73,176,177],{"class":162},"    public",[73,179,180],{"class":171}," String",[73,182,183],{"class":171}," father;\n",[73,185,186,188,190],{"class":75,"line":94},[73,187,177],{"class":162},[73,189,180],{"class":171},[73,191,192],{"class":171}," mother;\n",[73,194,195,199,202,205,208,211],{"class":75,"line":100},[73,196,198],{"class":197},"sj_SG","    Home",[73,200,201],{"class":171},"(String ",[73,203,204],{"class":165},"a",[73,206,207],{"class":171},", String ",[73,209,210],{"class":165},"b",[73,212,213],{"class":171},") {\n",[73,215,216,219,222],{"class":75,"line":106},[73,217,218],{"class":171},"        father ",[73,220,221],{"class":162},"=",[73,223,224],{"class":171}," a;\n",[73,226,227,230,232],{"class":75,"line":112},[73,228,229],{"class":171},"        mother ",[73,231,221],{"class":162},[73,233,234],{"class":171}," b;\n",[73,236,237],{"class":75,"line":118},[73,238,239],{"class":171},"    }\n",[73,241,242,244,247,250],{"class":75,"line":124},[73,243,177],{"class":162},[73,245,246],{"class":162}," void",[73,248,249],{"class":197}," myFather",[73,251,252],{"class":171},"(){\n",[73,254,255,258,261,264,268,271],{"class":75,"line":130},[73,256,257],{"class":171},"        System.out.",[73,259,260],{"class":197},"println",[73,262,263],{"class":171},"(",[73,265,267],{"class":266},"sTRMh","\"my father is \"",[73,269,270],{"class":162}," +",[73,272,273],{"class":171}," father);\n",[73,275,277],{"class":75,"line":276},11,[73,278,239],{"class":171},[73,280,282],{"class":75,"line":281},12,[73,283,284],{"class":171},"}\n",[73,286,288],{"class":75,"line":287},13,[73,289,291],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":290},true,"\n",[73,293,295,298,301],{"class":75,"line":294},14,[73,296,297],{"class":162},"public",[73,299,300],{"class":162}," class",[73,302,303],{"class":165}," main\n",[73,305,307],{"class":75,"line":306},15,[73,308,172],{"class":171},[73,310,312,314,317,319,322,324,327,330,333],{"class":75,"line":311},16,[73,313,177],{"class":162},[73,315,316],{"class":162}," static",[73,318,246],{"class":162},[73,320,321],{"class":197}," main",[73,323,263],{"class":171},[73,325,326],{"class":162},"String",[73,328,329],{"class":171},"[] ",[73,331,332],{"class":165},"args",[73,334,335],{"class":171},")\n",[73,337,339],{"class":75,"line":338},17,[73,340,341],{"class":171},"    {\n",[73,343,345,348,351,354,357,360,362,365,368,371],{"class":75,"line":344},18,[73,346,347],{"class":171},"        Home",[73,349,350],{"class":171}," myHome",[73,352,353],{"class":162}," =",[73,355,356],{"class":162}," new",[73,358,359],{"class":197}," Home",[73,361,263],{"class":171},[73,363,364],{"class":266},"\"jack\"",[73,366,367],{"class":171},", ",[73,369,370],{"class":266},"\"judy\"",[73,372,373],{"class":171},");\n",[73,375,377,379,381,384],{"class":75,"line":376},19,[73,378,257],{"class":171},[73,380,260],{"class":197},[73,382,383],{"class":171},"(myHome.father); ",[73,385,387],{"class":386},"sQrFR","\u002F\u002F jack\n",[73,389,391,393,395,398],{"class":75,"line":390},20,[73,392,257],{"class":171},[73,394,260],{"class":197},[73,396,397],{"class":171},"(myHome.mother); ",[73,399,400],{"class":386},"\u002F\u002F mother\n",[73,402,404,407,410,413],{"class":75,"line":403},21,[73,405,406],{"class":171},"        myHome.",[73,408,409],{"class":197},"myFather",[73,411,412],{"class":171},"(); ",[73,414,415],{"class":386},"\u002F\u002F my father is jack\n",[73,417,419],{"class":75,"line":418},22,[73,420,239],{"class":171},[73,422,424],{"class":75,"line":423},23,[73,425,284],{"class":171},[17,427,428],{},"And if we rewrite that in JavaScript, it looks like this:",[64,430,434],{"className":431,"code":432,"language":433,"meta":69,"style":69},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","function Home(father, mother) {\n  this.father = father;\n  this.mother = mother;\n}\n\nHome.prototype.myFather = function() {\n  console.log('my father is ' + this.father);\n}\n\nconst myHome = new Home('Jack', 'Judy');\nconsole.log(myHome.father, myHome.mother);\u002F\u002F Jack Judy\nmyHome.myFather(); \u002F\u002F my father is jack\n","js",[21,435,436,455,468,479,483,487,510,531,535,539,564,577],{"__ignoreMap":69},[73,437,438,441,443,445,448,450,453],{"class":75,"line":76},[73,439,440],{"class":162},"function",[73,442,359],{"class":197},[73,444,263],{"class":171},[73,446,447],{"class":165},"father",[73,449,367],{"class":171},[73,451,452],{"class":165},"mother",[73,454,213],{"class":171},[73,456,457,461,464,466],{"class":75,"line":82},[73,458,460],{"class":459},"sCcAr","  this",[73,462,463],{"class":171},".father ",[73,465,221],{"class":162},[73,467,183],{"class":171},[73,469,470,472,475,477],{"class":75,"line":88},[73,471,460],{"class":459},[73,473,474],{"class":171},".mother ",[73,476,221],{"class":162},[73,478,192],{"class":171},[73,480,481],{"class":75,"line":94},[73,482,284],{"class":171},[73,484,485],{"class":75,"line":100},[73,486,291],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":290},[73,488,489,492,495,498,500,502,504,507],{"class":75,"line":106},[73,490,491],{"class":459},"Home",[73,493,494],{"class":171},".",[73,496,497],{"class":459},"prototype",[73,499,494],{"class":171},[73,501,409],{"class":197},[73,503,353],{"class":162},[73,505,506],{"class":162}," function",[73,508,509],{"class":171},"() {\n",[73,511,512,515,518,520,523,525,528],{"class":75,"line":112},[73,513,514],{"class":171},"  console.",[73,516,517],{"class":197},"log",[73,519,263],{"class":171},[73,521,522],{"class":266},"'my father is '",[73,524,270],{"class":162},[73,526,527],{"class":459}," this",[73,529,530],{"class":171},".father);\n",[73,532,533],{"class":75,"line":118},[73,534,284],{"class":171},[73,536,537],{"class":75,"line":124},[73,538,291],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":290},[73,540,541,544,546,548,550,552,554,557,559,562],{"class":75,"line":130},[73,542,543],{"class":162},"const",[73,545,350],{"class":459},[73,547,353],{"class":162},[73,549,356],{"class":162},[73,551,359],{"class":197},[73,553,263],{"class":171},[73,555,556],{"class":266},"'Jack'",[73,558,367],{"class":171},[73,560,561],{"class":266},"'Judy'",[73,563,373],{"class":171},[73,565,566,569,571,574],{"class":75,"line":276},[73,567,568],{"class":171},"console.",[73,570,517],{"class":197},[73,572,573],{"class":171},"(myHome.father, myHome.mother);",[73,575,576],{"class":386},"\u002F\u002F Jack Judy\n",[73,578,579,582,584,586],{"class":75,"line":281},[73,580,581],{"class":171},"myHome.",[73,583,409],{"class":197},[73,585,412],{"class":171},[73,587,415],{"class":386},[17,589,590],{},"I won't get into why I picked Java as the example lol.",[17,592,593],{},[47,594],{"alt":595,"src":596},"Do you know the difference between Java and JavaScript?","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FPython\u002F%E5%BE%9E%20JavaScript%20%E8%A7%92%E5%BA%A6%E5%AD%B8%20Python\u002F1631889674093.png",[17,598,599,600,602,603,605],{},"The thing is, you can see Java uses ",[21,601,23],{}," to abstract a thing, a concept, and that ",[21,604,23],{}," can be inherited over and over.",[17,607,608,609,615],{},"But in the JavaScript example we just saw, JS can do something pretty similar too. So doesn't that make JavaScript object-oriented? In practice, it's a little awkward to call JavaScript straight-up OOP — it fits better as OOJS (Object-oriented JavaScript), since JavaScript is a prototype-based language. For a much better write-up, check out the ",[204,610,614],{"href":611,"rel":612},"https:\u002F\u002Fdeveloper.mozilla.org\u002Fen-US\u002Fdocs\u002FLearn\u002FJavaScript\u002FObjects\u002FObject-oriented_JS",[613],"nofollow","Object-oriented JavaScript for beginners"," chapter on MDN. What I'm doing here is just a quick chat — I'm not planning to go too deep on this.",[17,617,618,619,621,622,624,625,627],{},"Oh, side note: even though JavaScript introduced ",[21,620,23],{}," syntax in ECMAScript 6, under the hood that's just syntactic sugar over ",[21,623,497],{},". JavaScript still runs on prototypes deep down, so don't let the ",[21,626,23],{}," syntax sugar fool you.",[12,629,630],{"id":23},"Class",[17,632,633,634,636,637,639],{},"We've established that Python is an OOP language and we've talked through what object-oriented means, so now let's get to know how Python builds its own ",[21,635,23],{},". If you've written JavaScript ",[21,638,23],{}," syntax, this is going to feel familiar — almost cozy — because the syntax is really similar:",[64,641,645],{"className":642,"code":643,"language":644,"meta":69,"style":69},"language-py shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","class Home:\n  father = 'jack'\n","py",[21,646,647,652],{"__ignoreMap":69},[73,648,649],{"class":75,"line":76},[73,650,651],{},"class Home:\n",[73,653,654],{"class":75,"line":82},[73,655,656],{},"  father = 'jack'\n",[17,658,659,660,662],{},"Here's the JavaScript ",[21,661,23],{}," for comparison:",[64,664,666],{"className":431,"code":665,"language":433,"meta":69,"style":69},"class Home {\n  father = 'jack'\n}\n",[21,667,668,677,687],{"__ignoreMap":69},[73,669,670,672,674],{"class":75,"line":76},[73,671,23],{"class":162},[73,673,359],{"class":165},[73,675,676],{"class":171}," {\n",[73,678,679,682,684],{"class":75,"line":82},[73,680,681],{"class":165},"  father",[73,683,353],{"class":162},[73,685,686],{"class":266}," 'jack'\n",[73,688,689],{"class":75,"line":88},[73,690,284],{"class":171},[17,692,693],{},"Pretty close, right? Feeling that cozy familiarity?",[17,695,696],{},[47,697],{"alt":698,"src":699},"Can't tell what's Python and what's JavaScript anymore","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FPython\u002F%E5%BE%9E%20JavaScript%20%E8%A7%92%E5%BA%A6%E5%AD%B8%20Python\u002F1631891285003.png",[17,701,702],{},"So how do we instantiate the class we just declared? Not sure what instantiating means? In short, you can think of it as giving that abstract thing a sense of life. Let's see how it's done:",[64,704,706],{"className":642,"code":705,"language":644,"meta":69,"style":69},"class Home:\n  father = 'jack'\n\nmyHome = Home()\nprint(myHome.father) # jack\n",[21,707,708,712,716,720,725],{"__ignoreMap":69},[73,709,710],{"class":75,"line":76},[73,711,651],{},[73,713,714],{"class":75,"line":82},[73,715,656],{},[73,717,718],{"class":75,"line":88},[73,719,291],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":290},[73,721,722],{"class":75,"line":94},[73,723,724],{},"myHome = Home()\n",[73,726,727],{"class":75,"line":100},[73,728,729],{},"print(myHome.father) # jack\n",[17,731,732,733,736,737,739],{},"Super simple, right? We didn't even need ",[21,734,735],{},"new","! Nice and clean. (In JavaScript you have to use ",[21,738,735],{},".)",[17,741,742],{},[47,743],{"alt":744,"src":745},"I don't need new","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FPython\u002F%E5%BE%9E%20JavaScript%20%E8%A7%92%E5%BA%A6%E5%AD%B8%20Python\u002F1631891549603.png",[17,747,748,749,751],{},"But you might be thinking that when you create a ",[21,750,23],{},", you usually need to pass in some arguments to set the initial values or shape. With the dog example — when you bring a dog to life, you've got to give it a coat color and a breed, right?",[17,753,754],{},"In JavaScript that would look like this:",[64,756,758],{"className":431,"code":757,"language":433,"meta":69,"style":69},"class Home {\n   constructor(father) {\n    this.father = father;\n  }\n}\nconst myHome = new Home('jack');\nconsole.log(myHome.father); \u002F\u002F jack\n",[21,759,760,768,779,790,795,799,818],{"__ignoreMap":69},[73,761,762,764,766],{"class":75,"line":76},[73,763,23],{"class":162},[73,765,359],{"class":165},[73,767,676],{"class":171},[73,769,770,773,775,777],{"class":75,"line":82},[73,771,772],{"class":162},"   constructor",[73,774,263],{"class":171},[73,776,447],{"class":165},[73,778,213],{"class":171},[73,780,781,784,786,788],{"class":75,"line":88},[73,782,783],{"class":459},"    this",[73,785,463],{"class":171},[73,787,221],{"class":162},[73,789,183],{"class":171},[73,791,792],{"class":75,"line":94},[73,793,794],{"class":171},"  }\n",[73,796,797],{"class":75,"line":100},[73,798,284],{"class":171},[73,800,801,803,805,807,809,811,813,816],{"class":75,"line":106},[73,802,543],{"class":162},[73,804,350],{"class":459},[73,806,353],{"class":162},[73,808,356],{"class":162},[73,810,359],{"class":197},[73,812,263],{"class":171},[73,814,815],{"class":266},"'jack'",[73,817,373],{"class":171},[73,819,820,822,824,826],{"class":75,"line":112},[73,821,568],{"class":171},[73,823,517],{"class":197},[73,825,383],{"class":171},[73,827,387],{"class":386},[17,829,830,831,834,835,838,839,841,842,844,845,847,848,850],{},"So what about Python? Does Python use ",[21,832,833],{},"constructor"," too? Python mainly uses the ",[21,836,837],{},"__init__"," function. Every ",[21,840,23],{}," has an ",[21,843,837],{},", just like in JavaScript every ",[21,846,23],{}," has a ",[21,849,833],{}," you can use. So it ends up looking like this:",[64,852,854],{"className":642,"code":853,"language":644,"meta":69,"style":69},"class Home:\n  def __init__ (self, father):\n    self.father = father\n\nmyHome = Home('jack')\nprint(myHome.father) # jack\n",[21,855,856,860,865,870,874,879],{"__ignoreMap":69},[73,857,858],{"class":75,"line":76},[73,859,651],{},[73,861,862],{"class":75,"line":82},[73,863,864],{},"  def __init__ (self, father):\n",[73,866,867],{"class":75,"line":88},[73,868,869],{},"    self.father = father\n",[73,871,872],{"class":75,"line":94},[73,873,291],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":290},[73,875,876],{"class":75,"line":100},[73,877,878],{},"myHome = Home('jack')\n",[73,880,881],{"class":75,"line":106},[73,882,729],{},[17,884,885,886,889,890,892,893,896,897,899,900,902,903,905,906,908,909,913],{},"Right about now you're probably puzzled about what ",[21,887,888],{},"self"," is inside ",[21,891,837],{},". You can think of it as JavaScript's ",[21,894,895],{},"this"," inside a ",[21,898,833],{}," — but whatever you do, don't mix up Python's ",[21,901,888],{}," with JavaScript's ",[21,904,888],{},". As it happens, I recently wrote a piece on what JavaScript's ",[21,907,888],{}," actually is, so I'll recommend it as a ",[204,910,912],{"href":911},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20210914\u002F473800036\u002F","reference"," (article in Mandarin).",[17,915,916,917,919,920,923,924,926,927,929,930,932,933,935,936,939,940,943],{},"OK, back to Python. So Python's ",[21,918,888],{}," points to ",[21,921,922],{},"class Home"," itself, and every time you create a ",[21,925,23],{},", Python automatically calls the ",[21,928,837],{}," function (same as JavaScript, which automatically calls the ",[21,931,833],{},"). You don't strictly have to name it ",[21,934,888],{}," either — you could call it something else, like ",[21,937,938],{},"hello"," or ",[21,941,942],{},"ray",":",[64,945,947],{"className":642,"code":946,"language":644,"meta":69,"style":69},"class Home:\n  def __init__ (ray, father):\n    ray.father = father\n\nmyHome = Home('jack')\nprint(myHome.father) # jack\n",[21,948,949,953,958,963,967,971],{"__ignoreMap":69},[73,950,951],{"class":75,"line":76},[73,952,651],{},[73,954,955],{"class":75,"line":82},[73,956,957],{},"  def __init__ (ray, father):\n",[73,959,960],{"class":75,"line":88},[73,961,962],{},"    ray.father = father\n",[73,964,965],{"class":75,"line":94},[73,966,291],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":290},[73,968,969],{"class":75,"line":100},[73,970,878],{},[73,972,973],{"class":75,"line":106},[73,974,729],{},[17,976,977,978,980],{},"That said, I'd recommend sticking with ",[21,979,888],{},". Pick some weird name and you might get invited out for a \"friendly chat\" over coffee.",[17,982,983,984,986,987,989,990,992],{},"Next, similar to Java, we write our method functions inside the ",[21,985,23],{},". But heads up here: remember to pass ",[21,988,888],{}," into the method, otherwise you won't be able to access the ",[21,991,23],{},"'s own attributes:",[64,994,996],{"className":642,"code":995,"language":644,"meta":69,"style":69},"class Home:\n  def __init__ (self, father):\n    self.father = father\n  def myFather(self):\n    print('my father is ' + self.father)\n\nmyHome = Home('jack')\nprint(myHome.father) # jack\nmyHome.myFather() # my father is jack\n",[21,997,998,1002,1006,1010,1015,1020,1024,1028,1032],{"__ignoreMap":69},[73,999,1000],{"class":75,"line":76},[73,1001,651],{},[73,1003,1004],{"class":75,"line":82},[73,1005,864],{},[73,1007,1008],{"class":75,"line":88},[73,1009,869],{},[73,1011,1012],{"class":75,"line":94},[73,1013,1014],{},"  def myFather(self):\n",[73,1016,1017],{"class":75,"line":100},[73,1018,1019],{},"    print('my father is ' + self.father)\n",[73,1021,1022],{"class":75,"line":106},[73,1023,291],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":290},[73,1025,1026],{"class":75,"line":112},[73,1027,878],{},[73,1029,1030],{"class":75,"line":118},[73,1031,729],{},[73,1033,1034],{"class":75,"line":124},[73,1035,1036],{},"myHome.myFather() # my father is jack\n",[17,1038,1039],{},"And if you want to modify an attribute on Home, that's dead easy too — same as modifying any object property:",[64,1041,1043],{"className":642,"code":1042,"language":644,"meta":69,"style":69},"class Home:\n  def __init__ (self, father):\n    self.father = father\n  def myFather(self):\n    print('my father is ' + self.father)\n\nmyHome = Home('jack')\nprint(myHome.father) # jack\nmyHome.myFather() # my father is jack\nmyHome.father = 'Ray'\nprint(myHome.father) # Ray\n",[21,1044,1045,1049,1053,1057,1061,1065,1069,1073,1077,1081,1086],{"__ignoreMap":69},[73,1046,1047],{"class":75,"line":76},[73,1048,651],{},[73,1050,1051],{"class":75,"line":82},[73,1052,864],{},[73,1054,1055],{"class":75,"line":88},[73,1056,869],{},[73,1058,1059],{"class":75,"line":94},[73,1060,1014],{},[73,1062,1063],{"class":75,"line":100},[73,1064,1019],{},[73,1066,1067],{"class":75,"line":106},[73,1068,291],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":290},[73,1070,1071],{"class":75,"line":112},[73,1072,878],{},[73,1074,1075],{"class":75,"line":118},[73,1076,729],{},[73,1078,1079],{"class":75,"line":124},[73,1080,1036],{},[73,1082,1083],{"class":75,"line":130},[73,1084,1085],{},"myHome.father = 'Ray'\n",[73,1087,1088],{"class":75,"line":276},[73,1089,1090],{},"print(myHome.father) # Ray\n",[17,1092,1093],{},"There's also deleting attributes and methods from a class, and so on:",[64,1095,1097],{"className":642,"code":1096,"language":644,"meta":69,"style":69},"class Home:\n  def __init__ (self, father):\n    self.father = father\n  def myFather(self):\n    print('my father is ' + self.father)\n\nmyHome = Home('jack')\nprint(myHome.father) # jack\nmyHome.myFather() # my father is jack\n\nmyHome.father = 'Ray'\nprint(myHome.father) # Ray\n\ndel myHome.father\ndel myHome\n",[21,1098,1099,1103,1107,1111,1115,1119,1123,1127,1131,1135,1139,1143,1147,1151,1156],{"__ignoreMap":69},[73,1100,1101],{"class":75,"line":76},[73,1102,651],{},[73,1104,1105],{"class":75,"line":82},[73,1106,864],{},[73,1108,1109],{"class":75,"line":88},[73,1110,869],{},[73,1112,1113],{"class":75,"line":94},[73,1114,1014],{},[73,1116,1117],{"class":75,"line":100},[73,1118,1019],{},[73,1120,1121],{"class":75,"line":106},[73,1122,291],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":290},[73,1124,1125],{"class":75,"line":112},[73,1126,878],{},[73,1128,1129],{"class":75,"line":118},[73,1130,729],{},[73,1132,1133],{"class":75,"line":124},[73,1134,1036],{},[73,1136,1137],{"class":75,"line":130},[73,1138,291],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":290},[73,1140,1141],{"class":75,"line":276},[73,1142,1085],{},[73,1144,1145],{"class":75,"line":281},[73,1146,1090],{},[73,1148,1149],{"class":75,"line":287},[73,1150,291],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":290},[73,1152,1153],{"class":75,"line":294},[73,1154,1155],{},"del myHome.father\n",[73,1157,1158],{"class":75,"line":306},[73,1159,1160],{},"del myHome\n",[17,1162,1163],{},"Just note that once you've deleted something, it can't be called anymore.",[17,1165,1166,1167,1169,1170,1172,1173,1176],{},"The last pattern is a slightly special case. Normally a ",[21,1168,23],{}," body can't be empty, but if you've got a special situation where you need an empty ",[21,1171,23],{},", you can use the ",[21,1174,1175],{},"pass"," keyword to avoid an error:",[64,1178,1180],{"className":642,"code":1179,"language":644,"meta":69,"style":69},"class Home:\n  pass\n",[21,1181,1182,1186],{"__ignoreMap":69},[73,1183,1184],{"class":75,"line":76},[73,1185,651],{},[73,1187,1188],{"class":75,"line":82},[73,1189,1190],{},"  pass\n",[17,1192,1193,1194,1197],{},"Otherwise you'd typically get this error: \"",[21,1195,1196],{},"IndentationError: expected an indented block","\".",[17,1199,1200,1201,1203],{},"And since this chapter already brought up ",[21,1202,23],{},", the next one can't dodge the topic of inheritance.",[12,1205,1207],{"id":1206},"references","References",[1209,1210,1211,1217],"ul",{},[1212,1213,1214],"li",{},[204,1215,614],{"href":611,"rel":1216},[613],[1212,1218,1219],{},[204,1220,1223],{"href":1221,"rel":1222},"https:\u002F\u002Fen.wikipedia.org\u002Fwiki\u002FObject-oriented_programming",[613],"Object-oriented programming",[12,1225,1227],{"id":1226},"a-word-from-the-author","A Word From the Author",[17,1229,1230],{},"Lately my Mac has been acting up — out of nowhere the fans spin up like a plane about to take off. Is it... hinting I should switch to the M1 already? QQ?",[12,1232,1234],{"id":1233},"about-the-bunnies","About the Bunnies",[1209,1236,1237,1244,1252,1260],{},[1212,1238,1239],{},[204,1240,1243],{"href":1241,"rel":1242},"https:\u002F\u002Ftailwindcss.tw",[613],"Tailwind CSS Taiwan Official Site",[1212,1245,1246,1251],{},[204,1247,1250],{"href":1248,"rel":1249},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002Ftailwindcss.tw",[613],"Tailwind CSS Taiwan"," (Faceboo